\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
DM-nucleon interaction on Pulsar approach to explain AMS-Fermi anomaly
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that pulsars are a more natural explanation of AMS and Fermi data,
 we can look for differents possibilities to understand the nature of DM.
 Maybe, we can prove DM-SM interactions by looking at the interactions of
 cosmic rays and dm and how this can affect the data of these experiments.
 What is the cosmic-ray DM cross section that is compatible with light DM
 constrain? is multimessenger analysis compatible with this level of interaction
 at the cosmological level? are AMS and Fermi complementary measurements
 sensible to the allowed cross section? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A potential scenario may require no-null DM nucleon interactions in order
 to improve the explanation of AMS-Fermi data, while at the same time been
 potentially detectable with current or feasible technology in the context
 of DM direct detection experiments.
 Although optimistic, this desired output points in the direction of coordinatin
g the efforts of different experiments to search for DM, which can be applied
 in different experimental setups.
 For example, depending on the outputs related to this particular approach,
 we could apply the same strategy to to other experimental tandems, including
 CTA.
\end_layout

\end_body
